## 4. The "Hand Feel" Experience

- Impact Sensation
    - Hardness Words: Medium-soft, plush, and highly responsive. It feels closer to 42-44 degrees despite the official 45-degree rating.
    - Feedback: Clear, vibrating feedback on flat hits; can feel slightly vague on very thin brush contacts.
    - Hold vs. Release: Very quick release (bouncy). The ball does not linger long on the topsheet.
    - Dwell Time: Short-to-medium; grabs the ball just enough for a drive, but ejects it quickly.

- Sound/Click
    - Exceptional. Produces a loud, sharp metallic "tock" on hard impacts, highly reminiscent of the speed-glue era.

---

## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Can work, but carries a high risk of "bottoming out" on heavy impacts due to the soft sponge.
    - Inner Carbon: Excellent pairing. The wood outer plies add necessary dwell time, while the inner carbon supports the flat hits.
    - All-Wood: Highly recommended (e.g., 5-ply or classic 7-ply). Enhances control, maximizes spin potential, and complements the flat-hitting nature perfectly.
    - Mismatch Cases: Extremely hard outer-carbon blades (e.g., thick Tamca 5000) make it feel too mushy, hollow, and unpredictable.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Only recommended for developing players, flat-hitters, or those who do not rely on extreme spin to win points.
    - Backhand: Highly recommended. Perfect for the fast, punchy, blocking-oriented backhand game.

